article.headline: S. Utah 15, North Dakota 14
article.story: EDS: Optional. ADDs details and QUOTES. GRAND FORKS, N.D. -- Cody Stone's fortunes turned dramatically in the fourth quarter in leading Southern Utah to a come-from-behind 15-14 Great West Conference football victory over North Dakota Saturday. The Southern Utah quarterback threw four interceptions, but he had two touchdown tosses in the fourth quarter to rally the Thunderbids, who trailed 14-0 at halftime and 14-3 after three quarters. The winner was a 16-yard strike to Fesi Sitaki with 1:14 remaining to complete a 56-yard drive kept alive by a roughing-the-passer penalty with 2:22 left. Stone also threw a 22-yard touchdown pass to Tysson Boots early in the fourth quarter. Steve Pulver's 44-yard field goal gave the Thunderbirds their first points. "You usually don't win, much less be in a close game, when your team has four interceptions and a lost fumble," Stone said. "But our defense kept getting us the ball back in good shape and we took what they gave us on offense." UND seemed in control at halftime with a 14-0 lead behind two long drives. A 7-play, 80-yard drive was capped by a 17-yard swing pass from Danny Feund to running back Brandon Brady for a 7-0 lead. After Rory's Menke's interception, the Sioux went 78 yards on seven plays for a 14-0 halftime lead. Freund found Brady Trenbeath over the middle for an 11-yard touchdown. But the Sioux were held to three first downs, minus-3 yards rushing and 87 yards of total offense in the second half by the Thunderbirds' active defense. Freund was sacked five times in the game. "We allowed 15 points and that should win a game here," UND coach Chris Mussman said. "Our defense made stops but our offense just couldn't generate anything. It was a frustrating, frustrating, frustrating second half of football." Freund completed 17 of 25 passes for 186 yards, with two interceptions. Josh Murray led UND rushers with 16 carries for 83 yards, but didn't net any yardage in the second half. Stone was 21 of 41 passing for 250 yards while Daryl Brown led SU rushers with 70 yards on 18 carries. Southern Utah (1-2 in the conference, 4-5 overall) went 0-11 last season, including a 37-10 loss to UND. "To get a conference win and a road win is big for this program," Stone said. UND fell to 5-4 overall, 0-2 in the conference and 1-4 against fellow Division I Football Championship Series opponents.
